WEBVTT

00:00.226 --> 00:08.776
As we move from gathering to listening, our scripture reading today is from the book of John chapter three, verses 16 to 20.

00:10.218 --> 00:19.569
For God so loved the world that he gave us one and only son, that whoever believes in him shall not perish, but have eternal life.

00:20.910 --> 00:27.698
For God did not send his son into the world to condemn the world, but to save the world through him

00:28.770 --> 00:39.600
Whoever believes in him is not condemned, but whoever does not believe stands condemned already because they have not believed in the name of God's one and only son.

00:41.001 --> 00:42.062
This is the verdict.

00:42.983 --> 00:50.270
Light has come into the world, but people love darkness instead of light because their deeds were evil.

00:51.391 --> 00:58.738
Everyone who does evil hates the light and will not come into the light for fear that their deeds will be exposed.

00:59.522 --> 01:00.924
This is the word of the Lord.

01:01.685 --> 01:02.706
Thanks be to God.

01:17.885 --> 01:19.827
Hey fam, good to be home with you.

01:24.073 --> 01:28.338
You know, it's wild.

01:28.450 --> 01:29.731
how things work out.

01:31.894 --> 01:40.003
When my family decided to move to Spokane, which is beautiful, by the way, it turns out it actually is beautiful.

01:40.043 --> 01:40.723
You should come visit.

01:42.665 --> 01:57.842
Pete and I were talking, and I'm like, man, it wouldn't be fun if we could continue this rhythm of life together, even from afar, and maybe from time to time, I could come back and talk about

01:58.050 --> 02:08.860
what I'm seeing in this world as it's breaking apart and what it's like to be moving with people who are trying to figure out what it means to put it back together.

02:08.980 --> 02:12.384
And so we put November the 5th on the books.

02:12.964 --> 02:16.768
And we're in a series here on the whole gospel.

02:17.068 --> 02:27.538
And the invitation a couple months ago was to preach on love, which I love to preach on love.

02:29.570 --> 02:47.352
You know, I'm sitting in front of you right now with both the relief to be home and with a sense of shame for having been able to leave a war zone.

02:48.213 --> 02:54.000
And some of you know that my work with global immersion takes me into war zones as a way of my life.

02:54.641 --> 02:59.026
Whether battlefields or boardrooms, I'm moving into this space.

02:59.234 --> 03:01.337
with tools to heal rather than to win.

03:02.818 --> 03:10.849
And I got evacuated three weeks ago, and we'll talk a lot more about that.

03:10.889 --> 03:17.737
I really do hope you come to the forum, because I think a holistic, more pro-human understanding of this crisis is important for all of us.

03:18.378 --> 03:20.621
And we'll talk more about that there.

03:20.661 --> 03:28.050
But I got evacuated three weeks ago, and I landed in Boston.

03:28.962 --> 03:31.605
And the sun is rising and everything is calm.

03:33.867 --> 03:35.528
And I'm going through customs.

03:37.470 --> 03:41.053
And the customs agent, he says, you know, what's your name?

03:41.134 --> 03:43.536
And how long were you in Israel?

03:43.856 --> 03:47.019
And then he said, what's the nature of your work?

03:48.881 --> 03:54.847
And I said, well, I kind of live at the intersection of faith, leadership, and peacemaking.

03:54.907 --> 03:58.450
My work is peacemaking and conflict transformation.

03:58.658 --> 04:01.863
And he looks at me and he goes, then why did you leave?

04:04.026 --> 04:06.910
And he slides my passport back to me.

04:07.090 --> 04:18.506
And I think in the three weeks since that moment I'm beginning to find my bearings in terms of why I left and why I'm here.

04:18.606 --> 04:26.738
And it's really about companioning American Christians in our liberation from a religion that dominates to a faith that restores.

04:27.618 --> 04:34.548
because the world is dying because we have been socialized into a religion that dominates.

04:34.588 --> 04:43.100
We've been socialized into fidelity into a religion that says violence is endorsed by God so long as it serves us.

04:46.345 --> 04:47.447
So why did I leave?

04:47.487 --> 04:55.218
I think I left to continue the work of companioning us and others in this perilous pilgrimage.

04:55.618 --> 05:01.344
So I want to offer some thoughts out of about love then as it relates to that.

05:01.404 --> 05:11.695
And I want to share some stories about love, what it looks like, what it felt like for me a couple of weeks ago in the Middle East.

05:11.715 --> 05:16.761
Because I learned a thing or two about whole gospel kind of like full gospel love.

05:16.781 --> 05:25.170
Like the kind of love that's not warm and affectionate, but like it's the kind of love that's like full gospel, like, you know, boundary.

05:25.314 --> 05:30.767
breaking solidarity, making captive, liberating, creative, and costly kind of love.

05:30.787 --> 05:38.305
I learned something more about this in a war zone, and I'd love to share some of those stories with you.

05:38.366 --> 05:41.874
A month ago today, I was in Scotland.

05:42.850 --> 05:53.246
And I was speaking at a book festival where they had invited other authors from around the world that are writing on the themes of conflict and peacemaking.

05:53.286 --> 06:06.546
And so I got to spend time in Scotland of all places in like the greenest hills I've ever seen inhabited by the bushiest sheep I've ever seen in my life, like the pinnacle of tranquility.

06:06.818 --> 06:25.239
at least on the surface level, and I'm speaking at this gig, and I'm sharing stages with other peacemakers from around the planet, Northern Ireland, South Africa, war correspondents who, like me, are very compelled to enter into conflict, and use whatever tools that are in our hands to bring an end to violence.

06:26.441 --> 06:34.610
And there's a custom at this particular book festival where every day ends with what's called Books at Bedtime,

06:35.330 --> 06:37.973
And it is exactly what you think it would be.

06:37.993 --> 06:42.277
It's an author is invited to choose their favorite children's book.

06:42.998 --> 06:48.744
And then like hundreds of people climb into this tent in like the most comfortable clothes they have at nine o'clock at night.

06:48.784 --> 06:52.607
And everybody has like London fog tea and their homemade mugs.

06:52.768 --> 06:56.031
And then an author reads a story.

06:56.912 --> 07:03.058
And the story that I read is the old turtle and the broken truth.

07:04.962 --> 07:08.787
Now this is a story and let me share a little bit of it with you.

07:08.807 --> 07:16.618
It's a story about a beautiful truth that fell from the heavens and as it entered into earth, it broke into pieces.

07:18.601 --> 07:31.218
And in the beginning of the story, the animals find a part of this truth and they play with it and they experiment and they try it on and they recognize it just doesn't work for them.

07:32.802 --> 07:42.918
So it gets kind of covered by debris and over time, humanity finds this partial truth and they're able to decipher the truth etched into it.

07:42.938 --> 07:47.586
The truth that they discovered said, I am loved.

07:50.831 --> 07:57.842
And the story says this, what they found, they called the truth.

07:59.202 --> 08:12.621
The truth made the people feel good and proud and strong, but soon they also began to feel fear and even anger toward those who were not like themselves and did not share their truth.

08:14.163 --> 08:24.818
The other beings and other people of the lovely land seemed less and less important, and the language of the breezes was hardly ever heard anymore.

08:26.850 --> 08:35.038
Time passed and other people said, we must have this great truth for ourselves, for with it comes happiness and power.

08:35.098 --> 08:47.630
And many battles were fought and the broken truth was won and lost, won and lost, over and over again, but such was its power and beauty that no one ever doubted it.

08:47.710 --> 08:52.315
And when they were without it, they felt a great emptiness where their truth had been.

08:52.335 --> 08:55.858
The stones and trees suffered.

08:57.186 --> 09:04.755
The breezes and waters suffered, and the animals and the earth, and most of all, the people suffered.

09:07.258 --> 09:09.100
And then there's this little girl.

09:11.382 --> 09:24.978
And this little girl had been shaped by a life of violence, ideologies and theologies that said it's okay to reach for power rather than the hand of one another.

09:25.410 --> 09:35.162
There's a little girl who dares to believe that there's a hopeful alternative to the nonsense of power and violence and domination and control and conquering.

09:35.182 --> 09:40.268
And so she takes a journey because she knows that a journey is the only thing that's gonna transform her.

09:41.069 --> 09:42.931
She wants to find the old turtle.

09:44.533 --> 09:48.117
And so she navigates through this winding hero's journey.

09:48.157 --> 09:51.922
She's a true heroine being transformed by the journey.

09:53.474 --> 10:05.087
Eventually she finds the old turtle and she says to her, where I live, the earth is sore and people are suffering.

10:06.729 --> 10:09.211
Battles are fought over and over again.

10:11.153 --> 10:14.077
People say it's always been this way and will never change.

10:14.417 --> 10:15.899
Can it change, old turtle?

10:16.980 --> 10:18.101
Can we make it change?

10:20.604 --> 10:22.706
And then old turtle begins to talk to her

10:23.810 --> 10:32.279
and shares with her this truth, they wore because they have organized their lives around a partial truth.

10:34.381 --> 10:37.724
They've organized their lives around a partial truth.

10:39.466 --> 10:48.055
The old turtle says, it is because it is so close to a great whole truth that it has such beauty and that the people love it so.

10:49.736 --> 10:51.538
It is the lost portion

10:52.002 --> 10:57.329
of that broken truth that the people need if the world is to be made whole again.

10:57.369 --> 11:08.362
Little did I know that within days of reading that children's book, I would be living in the themes of that book.

11:12.988 --> 11:17.874
My work with global immersion, we're a peacemaking training organization.

11:18.882 --> 11:20.225
And we'd really do three things.

11:20.266 --> 11:21.348
We mediate conflict.

11:21.388 --> 11:24.637
We form conflict competent leaders, teams, and cultures.

11:25.138 --> 11:31.314
And then we forge communities of everyday peacemakers like Antioch to join God in repairing the world.

11:32.866 --> 11:40.300
Part of the work that we've done over the last 12 years has involved building delegations of US-based folk and bringing them into the epicenter of conflict.

11:40.380 --> 11:40.681
Why?

11:40.721 --> 11:50.098
Because if you want to learn about peace, conflict is the best classroom in the world because the best teachers on the planet are embedded in the trenches of those conflicts waging peace.

11:50.530 --> 11:52.352
Israel Palestine is one of those spaces.

11:52.392 --> 12:11.875
So for 12 years, my learning curve has been very steep in understanding not only the geopolitical history of that particular conflict, but the ways in which theologies and ideologies, especially American evangelical theologies and ideologies, have been creating a catastrophe in the pursuit of our dream.

12:12.916 --> 12:14.898
We'll talk a little bit more about that this afternoon.

12:17.666 --> 12:20.690
I haven't been in Israel and Palestine since a global pandemic.

12:21.890 --> 12:36.903
We were in the process of training a delegation of leaders from Westside here in Bend, because they have a passion as a congregation to take a journey toward becoming an instrument of peace, not only in this area alongside Antioch, but within their denomination.

12:36.923 --> 12:44.570
So the play was, let's build a delegation of leaders from within this congregation, and let's train together in the work of peacemaking.

12:45.010 --> 12:51.876
Let's become faith-based, Jesus-centering folk who know what it means to wear crosses rather than wield

12:51.856 --> 12:52.056
them.

12:52.957 --> 13:01.166
The hope was that we would build an engine room of reconciliation that would then guide the transformation of that congregation into an instrument of peace.

13:01.186 --> 13:05.711
And so I was going to be taking them with me into Israel, Palestine as a part of their training.

13:06.852 --> 13:12.859
Now, because I haven't been there since a global pandemic, I wanted to go just a couple days early because usually when I'm there, I've got people with me.

13:12.899 --> 13:19.666
And I wanted to chill with my friends, Israelis and Palestinians, the peacemakers who are embedded in that crisis without folks with me.

13:19.970 --> 13:27.839
So I arrived on October the 5th, and I took a car to the West Bank, which is the Palestinian territory.

13:27.859 --> 13:35.268
You got to make it through some checkpoints in order to get there because my dear friend, brother and sister Milad and Minar, who they're my brother and sister, they're married to one another.

13:36.109 --> 13:38.331
I wanted to see them.

13:38.572 --> 13:39.913
I wanted to spend time with them.

13:39.953 --> 13:41.395
They live in a city called Bethany.

13:41.415 --> 13:47.602
And when we got there, I learned that October 6th was Minar's birthday.

13:48.546 --> 13:52.392
And so ever the hype guy, I'm like, what are we going to do?

13:52.432 --> 13:59.443
And she says, I'm so glad that you asked because I was going to actually ask you a favor.

14:01.005 --> 14:11.762
Her dream, since she was a little girl, was to ride her bike from Bethany, which is on the backside of the Mount of Olives, to Jericho.

14:13.570 --> 14:30.898
Now the only way that you can ride your bike from Bethany, which is one of the most heavily occupied areas in the West Bank, to Jericho, is through a number of checkpoints that are manned by ideologically entrenched young people with guns who are suffering their own kind of trauma.

14:32.034 --> 14:34.738
And you have to ride what's called the Jericho road.

14:34.778 --> 14:37.041
Is that a familiar road to us as Jesus people?

14:37.101 --> 14:37.241
Right.

14:37.562 --> 14:41.046
Good Samaritan, there's a catastrophe that happens on the Jericho road.

14:41.066 --> 14:45.152
You gotta ride your bike on the Jericho road to get from Bethany to Jericho.

14:46.173 --> 14:51.460
And then right now, that road takes you by the largest Israeli settlement in the West Bank.

14:53.403 --> 14:59.812
And she knows, and her husband, Millad, I'll show you a picture of him in a second, he's like a Armenian God.

15:00.313 --> 15:01.394
I mean, just the,

15:01.954 --> 15:03.897
best looking human being I've ever met.

15:05.379 --> 15:13.430
Tall and strong and strapping and for those reasons he is humiliated by the Zionist occupation of his land.

15:15.032 --> 15:21.681
They take every chance to humiliate him and to shame him and physically manhandle him.

15:23.643 --> 15:31.474
And she knows that there's no way that she's going to live this dream riding her bike next to him.

15:33.346 --> 15:35.168
And that's what she says, and Millaud understands.

15:35.208 --> 15:35.909
He's the same way.

15:36.450 --> 15:39.914
She goes, I can't do this ride next to him, but with you.

15:40.015 --> 15:41.517
And then she goes like this, but with you.

15:41.537 --> 15:51.590
I think we can make this ride.

15:57.457 --> 15:58.098
And so,

15:58.882 --> 16:00.244
I'm like, absolutely, I'm in.

16:00.324 --> 16:03.227
And I look at Milada, I'm like, about how far is this bike ride?

16:04.148 --> 16:10.036
And says someone who has never ridden a bike because he's ridden a bike.

16:10.056 --> 16:13.079
He's never ridden a bike that distance because he can't.

16:14.621 --> 16:16.083
Not because he can't physically.

16:16.163 --> 16:23.272
He can't because of the structural violence that's in place that limits his ability to take a long bike ride.

16:27.617 --> 16:28.178
And so,

16:29.730 --> 16:32.132
He says it'll probably be about a 30 minute ride.

16:34.875 --> 16:37.718
It's a 40 kilometer bike ride.

16:40.441 --> 16:49.270
But he didn't know how to give me an accurate timing because it's an impossibility for him to take that ride.

16:51.632 --> 16:57.298
So the next morning, Milad and I, we go and we find some mountain bikes.

16:59.106 --> 17:07.747
And we grease up some chains and we put air in cracked tires and ride these bikes.

17:07.807 --> 17:17.010
And this is him taking a picture of the two of us as we're making our way from a local gas station to Miladim and ours home.

17:18.594 --> 17:24.103
And Menar and I begin this ride, and this is a picture of the two of us, just at the beginnings of our ride.

17:24.143 --> 17:26.387
I'm wearing a nice shirt, it's a familiar one, right?

17:27.128 --> 17:30.454
It's the jersey of our family, friends, right here, right?

17:31.616 --> 17:32.778
Ward on purpose, right?

17:33.960 --> 17:40.631
Like this is a moment of solidarity, but this is also a declaration of the world that I'm dreaming of.

17:43.375 --> 17:44.978
And we begin our ride.

17:46.082 --> 17:48.005
And y'all, it was 90 degrees.

17:48.525 --> 17:50.368
It was a 40 kilometer bike ride.

17:50.508 --> 17:54.994
We're on the clunkiest mountain bikes you've ever seen in your life riding on the Jericho Road.

17:55.055 --> 17:58.379
And it was one of the most memorable, phenomenal experiences of my life.

17:59.341 --> 18:09.735
A couple of things happened that I want to just lift up in my own expansion of the reach of my empathy and pro-human understanding of what's happening here.

18:09.815 --> 18:11.858
She's terrified of the settlers.

18:13.090 --> 18:22.979
But if I had a dollar for every settler that drove by honking their horns and cheering us on and offering us water, I would have been able to buy breakfast that morning for us all.

18:23.940 --> 18:24.341
It's cool.

18:25.301 --> 18:29.025
But I also recognized that there was a familiarity.

18:29.045 --> 18:34.290
There was a reason probably why they were encouraging us as we rode together.

18:36.192 --> 18:36.892
Here's the moment.

18:38.854 --> 18:42.898
We're riding, and I'm behind Menar.

18:43.330 --> 18:48.617
Here's someone who is living a childhood dream that she has never been able to do.

18:48.657 --> 19:10.866
And I happen to be riding behind her when she, and I don't know, I don't know how often she rides a bike, but like we're bombing down this, because on the Jericho road, you go from like a thousand feet above sea level to like 500 feet below sea level.

19:11.618 --> 19:17.612
You know, in my defense, there's a couple of nice climbs too, you know, but for the most part, you're just bombing.

19:17.652 --> 19:18.895
She's bombing.

19:20.077 --> 19:26.632
And I watch her release her handlebars and ride like this.

19:30.381 --> 19:30.802
Free.

19:43.106 --> 19:56.591
Love that day looked like leveraging the privilege etched into my body to ensure that in the midst of a lifelong nightmare, one of her dreams could come true.

19:59.096 --> 20:02.482
For one brief moment, she could live free.

20:07.650 --> 20:10.014
That's whole gospel love, and it changed me that day.

20:10.034 --> 20:19.630
It heightened my awareness of the privilege that I embody and taught me more about how to leverage it, all of it for the sake of another's liberation.

20:25.079 --> 20:34.354
That night, it was her birthday dinner, and in my home, whoever's birthday it is, gets to choose what the meal is, and they didn't have any real big

20:34.434 --> 20:35.395
birthday traditions.

20:35.435 --> 20:37.218
So I'm like, what are we going to make?

20:38.719 --> 20:41.683
And she said, how about chicken alfredo?

20:41.723 --> 20:50.214
And so Malad and I off we went again to try to find the ingredients for chicken alfredo.

20:50.494 --> 20:53.338
And we found it.

20:53.919 --> 20:57.063
And the two of us made chicken alfredo.

20:57.984 --> 21:02.770
But much to her chagrin, we forgot to pick up chicken.

21:03.266 --> 21:09.575
And she let us know how ridiculous it is to eat chicken Alfredo without chicken.

21:11.157 --> 21:19.668
And that evening we're sitting out, this is their backyard, and we're enjoying Alfredo.

21:22.793 --> 21:26.958
And let me say a few things about Bethany.

21:26.998 --> 21:29.682
Bethany is a place of restoration and resurrection.

21:31.074 --> 21:34.540
Bethany is the place where Mary and Martha and Lazarus lived.

21:36.723 --> 21:47.140
This is the place where Jesus would show up and let his hair down and engage in just some unrushed friend time feet up with some of his best friends.

21:49.063 --> 21:53.170
This is a place that's less than an hour's walk from the old city of Jerusalem.

21:53.986 --> 22:07.181
But because of structural violence and an occupation, it takes hours of driving to move through multiple checkpoints to get into Jerusalem if you have a permit to get in, literally on the backside of the Mount of Olive.

22:07.201 --> 22:21.618
So when Jesus is entering into Jerusalem on what we would call Palm Sunday, he's been hanging in Bethany with Mary, Martha and Lazarus, chilling out, probably leaning heavily onto them because he has a sense of what's about to happen.

22:21.794 --> 22:22.054
Right?

22:22.155 --> 22:32.330
And then he would have climbed up the backside of the Mount of Olives, overseeing the temple in the city and then lamented that Jerusalem did not know the things that made for peace.

22:34.173 --> 22:44.148
Where we're having birthday dinner and what you're looking at right now is what we could see and it's literally overlooking Lazarus' tomb because it's also a place of resurrection.

22:44.228 --> 22:48.114
Jesus raised his bro from the dead right there, you know?

22:50.530 --> 22:56.078
And as we're sitting there enjoying dinner, violence began to crescendo.

22:57.661 --> 23:02.227
Shouts and blasts and gas and gunfire and burning tires.

23:02.287 --> 23:05.552
And at first Milad and Menar were like, welcome to Friday night in Bethany.

23:06.594 --> 23:15.087
And every time, ah, man, every time another explosion would happen, Menar would say, ah, they celebrate my birthday.

23:15.147 --> 23:20.114
Which is a, that's trauma.

23:21.506 --> 23:26.693
to make light of explosions that are probably altering someone else's reality.

23:27.093 --> 23:31.619
The only way you can deal with it is with a little bit of humor.

23:34.863 --> 23:39.910
And then it went from this is Friday night in Bethany to this is different.

23:39.950 --> 23:41.011
Something is happening.

23:42.393 --> 23:43.314
We went inside.

23:45.698 --> 23:58.493
The next morning was October 7th and I awoke to missiles exploding in the sky above us and news that Hamas insurgents had broken through the walls that enclosed Gaza Strip and were murdering Israeli civilians.

24:00.715 --> 24:01.356
This is different.

24:02.597 --> 24:03.398
Something is happening.

24:05.741 --> 24:10.226
My friend, my lad, urged me to stay.

24:11.810 --> 24:16.982
Now, as a general rule, when I'm in war zones, I take my cues from the people who are on the ground.

24:18.886 --> 24:21.131
Somehow, somebody captured this image.

24:21.171 --> 24:27.506
I think it was Menar, and this is Melod and I talking about what are we going to do about this?

24:28.002 --> 24:30.125
Not only in terms of like, do I stay?

24:30.185 --> 24:30.786
Do I leave?

24:30.866 --> 24:48.470
But how do we leverage all of our resources right now in a way that can either awaken people's understanding to what's going on or can make sure that you as an organization remain resource to be able to wage peace and the trenches of what will probably be a really devastating war?

24:48.590 --> 24:50.853
So this is the conversation that we're having here.

24:51.154 --> 24:52.375
He's urging me to stay.

24:52.415 --> 24:57.362
He knew it would be dangerous to get from Bethany and to the checkpoints.

24:57.986 --> 25:01.813
He knew that everybody manning the checkpoints would be heavily triggered.

25:02.173 --> 25:05.239
This is an attack on the psyche of the Jewish soul.

25:05.299 --> 25:07.944
Everybody's going to be triggered.

25:07.984 --> 25:12.191
It's going to be dangerous to move through, and it will probably be really dangerous to be in Jerusalem.

25:13.634 --> 25:20.466
But he also knew that I had a delegation of US Americans landing into what was now a war zone.

25:22.018 --> 25:32.169
He knew that my work is to guide American Christians in a journey of liberation that carries significant implications, not only for his safety, but for his future.

25:33.050 --> 25:35.033
He knew I had to get to Jerusalem.

25:36.815 --> 25:50.450
So he calls one of his best friends and he gives him direct orders that you will do whatever it takes to get my friend out of the West Bank and into Jerusalem and

25:51.010 --> 25:56.137
If it gets dangerous, you are to bring him right back here, no questions asked.

26:00.183 --> 26:05.570
Love that day looked like their concern for my well-being while their own was being compromised.

26:07.353 --> 26:12.399
Love looked like an offer of unprecedented hospitality for as long as it was needed.

26:13.962 --> 26:20.050
Love looked like utilizing their network of relationships to position me where the work was most urgent.

26:21.442 --> 26:22.904
And it changed me that day.

26:25.188 --> 26:37.247
Love deepened our costly solidarity and emboldened me to keep taking huge risks to challenge the truthless Christianity that had made this violence inevitable.

26:43.016 --> 26:46.962
I got to Jerusalem and six of 10 were able to actually land on the ground.

26:49.314 --> 27:02.073
Together we were undone by the scale of terror inflicted on Israelis by Hamas insurgents and we held our breath in anticipation of the terror that Israeli power brokers would mobilize upon Gazans.

27:03.956 --> 27:06.540
And then we were stunned by its scale.

27:11.568 --> 27:15.914
My focus in that time was divided in six different directions.

27:17.657 --> 27:18.258
First,

27:19.010 --> 27:26.365
I had to pastor a small community of resilient leaders that were trying to find their heads and their hearts in an ever-changing environment.

27:28.228 --> 27:36.304
Second, I was there to train peacemakers, US-American peacemakers from within the context of a crisis.

27:36.966 --> 27:41.234
The training environment had shifted, but I was training them.

27:41.474 --> 27:49.082
Nonetheless, to be peacemakers who know what it means to grow a more holistic, pro-human understanding of what was unfolding.

27:50.563 --> 27:54.007
Third, I had to provide some triage therapy.

27:55.548 --> 28:01.254
For this, conflict was triggering and dislodging and disorienting.

28:02.996 --> 28:06.840
Fourth, I had to build plans to evacuate my people out of the country.

28:08.641 --> 28:09.202
Fifth,

28:09.698 --> 28:15.808
I had to care for and collaborate with my Israeli and Palestinian partners, now peacemakers embedded within the trenches of this war.

28:17.271 --> 28:25.084
And sixth, I had an opportunity to offer some commentary to Western Christians about what it was that we were witnessing.

28:27.268 --> 28:28.530
It's crazy, y'all.

28:28.834 --> 28:32.979
We would build a contingency for evacuation and within 30 minutes it would fall apart.

28:32.999 --> 28:46.457
So we had to build another contingency with fall apart, another another another and fall apart, fall apart, fall apart, all the while holding the unbelievable reality that because of our privilege and a blue passport, chances were very good.

28:46.517 --> 28:50.722
We would get out of the country while millions do not have that option.

28:51.904 --> 28:53.746
It's hard to hold that.

28:54.466 --> 28:58.492
But we worked hard to hold both of those realities at the same time.

28:58.632 --> 29:01.016
Finally, we built a contingency plan that held.

29:01.076 --> 29:01.837
We had tickets.

29:01.857 --> 29:04.541
We were going to evacuate my people through Jordan.

29:06.544 --> 29:13.254
And once tickets were in hand, I invited a Jerusalem-based Jewish peacemaker to sit with us.

29:13.355 --> 29:15.117
He's a historian and theologian.

29:16.479 --> 29:18.322
He joined us at the hotel.

29:18.402 --> 29:29.697
that we were staying at and I just invited him to share his experience of October 7th and what this moment unlocked in the soul and the psyche of the Jewish people.

29:32.801 --> 29:41.151
He reminded us that the Jewish people for millennia have been threatened with elimination, erasure.

29:42.833 --> 29:46.418
And in some moments in time, it's almost been successful.

29:48.322 --> 29:58.676
helped us understand that what happened on the seventh awakened a societal level PTSD at a DNA level inside of the Jewish community, our Jewish kin.

30:00.839 --> 30:02.822
And with that understanding, empathy grew.

30:02.842 --> 30:06.567
And we held him in his despair and grief.

30:06.647 --> 30:10.773
And then he held us as we asked questions imperfectly.

30:12.815 --> 30:15.519
And then he taught us the Jewish concept of makhloket.

30:16.420 --> 30:17.682
Really fun word to say.

30:17.954 --> 30:21.219
Right here, makhlokit.

30:21.239 --> 30:25.847
Makhlokit, the root of that term means part or particle.

30:27.469 --> 30:34.621
That root is also used in the words divide and share, whereas shalom, that means whole, wholeness.

30:35.242 --> 30:40.530
Makhlokit means righteous disagreement or constructive disagreement.

30:41.090 --> 30:48.099
It means that I, my experience and my perspective is as valid as your experience and your perspective.

30:48.139 --> 30:59.573
Makloka doesn't mean that we dominate one another and try to prove the superiority of our perspective and opinion, but rather we come to a table acknowledging that I am never fully right and always partially wrong.

31:01.015 --> 31:03.698
That my perspective is not 2020 vision.

31:04.450 --> 31:10.458
that the experiences and perspectives of my other's irritants and enemies are valid, even necessary.

31:10.538 --> 31:20.031
And our work, again, is not to dominate one another, but to listen and dialogue and disagree in the direction of a better, shared understanding.

31:20.071 --> 31:23.516
He said to win is to break with the tradition.

31:25.779 --> 31:34.130
And then he and I had a fishbowl conversation with my people listening in about how to win, to dominate, to control, to

31:34.242 --> 31:37.805
is to break with the essence of our traditions.

31:40.728 --> 31:45.853
As we're having that conversation, the air sirens, the air raid sirens begin to blare.

31:47.795 --> 31:51.759
Missiles and rockets are blowing up on top of, in the air above us again.

31:53.841 --> 31:59.367
He looks at me with a level of fear, and he said, does this hotel have a bomb shelter?

32:00.268 --> 32:00.668
We don't.

32:01.829 --> 32:02.770
We have a stairwell.

32:04.098 --> 32:06.181
So we're on the rooftop at this point.

32:06.261 --> 32:07.923
We all run to the stairwell.

32:07.943 --> 32:15.113
And as we're running, he reaches and he grabs my hand and he says, Jer, this is what happens when Makhlokit breaks down.

32:18.057 --> 32:22.243
We make our way to the very base of the stairwell.

32:23.805 --> 32:30.554
And I found myself with Israelis and Palestinians and internationals and friends in that moment.

32:30.594 --> 32:33.298
We experienced our shared humanity.

32:34.210 --> 32:36.093
We protected one another's dignity.

32:37.194 --> 32:39.637
We discovered our interdependence.

32:42.581 --> 32:44.864
And so love that day looked like an invitation.

32:44.924 --> 32:50.031
It looked like proximity to someone who was in pain and meeting him in his despair.

32:50.372 --> 32:54.097
It looked like holding space for imperfect curiosity.

32:54.217 --> 33:03.890
Love looked like strangers reaching for the hands of one another while the sounds of power made inevitable by people who reach for power is

33:04.002 --> 33:06.085
like the soundtrack of the moment.

33:10.270 --> 33:11.311
And here's what it did for me.

33:11.852 --> 33:15.336
Here's how that full gospel kind of love changed me in that moment.

33:17.318 --> 33:25.608
It caused me to fully break agreement with any way of organizing myself around a partial truth.

33:28.972 --> 33:30.354
So let's return to the old turtle.

33:33.506 --> 33:40.304
The old turtle said, quote, it's the lost portion of that broken truth that the people need if the world is to be made whole again.

33:40.344 --> 33:46.740
But where is the missing piece, asked the little girl, can we put the truth back together again?

33:46.780 --> 33:50.610
And after a while, the old turtle spoke again.

33:51.778 --> 34:04.892
The broken truth and life itself will be mended only when one person meets another, someone from a different place or a different face or different ways and sees and hears herself.

34:06.314 --> 34:13.422
Only then will the people know that every person, every being is important and that the world was made for each of us.

34:15.984 --> 34:21.170
For a long time then the two friends were quiet, high on their hill in the very center of the world.

34:21.890 --> 34:31.743
And in her heart the little girl thought she could see other people in other beautiful lands, people different from her own, but still somehow the people.

34:34.467 --> 34:37.731
Now, little one, it's time for you to go.

34:37.752 --> 34:47.184
To return to your people and tell them what you have seen and learned and help them mend their broken truth.

34:49.347 --> 34:51.410
Take this with you, settled turtle.

34:52.514 --> 34:54.356
as she placed something in the little girl's hand.

34:55.177 --> 34:58.121
I've saved it for a very long time for someone just like you."

35:00.083 --> 35:02.486
The little girl looked at what old turtle had given her.

35:03.487 --> 35:06.450
It was a kind of stone, a mysterious, beautiful stone.

35:06.530 --> 35:09.153
It was lovely to touch, and it made her feel good to hold it.

35:10.695 --> 35:13.478
She squeezed it tightly, then tucked it away for her journey.

35:13.719 --> 35:17.363
Thank you, old turtle, she said, and hugged her friend's great leathery neck.

35:18.905 --> 35:19.986
And then she started home.

35:21.506 --> 35:27.593
Once more, she traveled through the forest of finding out across the river of wondering why in the mountains of imagining.

35:28.734 --> 35:34.160
Crow led the way and again when the little girl grew tired, all her animal friends helped.

35:35.582 --> 35:43.671
She sometimes touched the stone old turtle had given her to renew her strength, and it took a long time, yet almost no time at all.

35:45.193 --> 35:46.194
And she was home.

35:47.874 --> 35:53.564
But it had been a very long journey, and those who take great journeys of the heart are changed.

35:55.467 --> 35:56.909
The people did not recognize her.

35:57.651 --> 36:00.175
And when she spoke, they did not understand.

36:01.918 --> 36:05.324
She told them of her journey, but the people could not follow her words.

36:05.684 --> 36:13.778
She spoke of a world made of small and gentle truths, of all the people being one people, but they could not catch her meaning.

36:14.914 --> 36:22.522
She explained about the broken truth and the need to make it whole, but the people did not believe her and could not understand.

36:22.582 --> 36:35.435
Finally, Crow, seeing all that had happened flew to the place high above the village where the great truth was kept, in a place where all could see it.

36:36.896 --> 36:42.322
He cawed and cawed in his loudest voice and suddenly the little girl knew what to do.

36:43.330 --> 36:45.273
She climbed to the high place herself.

36:46.114 --> 36:54.107
She took old turtle stone from her pocket and carefully added the missing piece to the old broken one.

36:56.230 --> 36:58.293
The fit was perfect.

37:01.979 --> 37:06.205
The people looked and looked and looked.

37:08.489 --> 37:11.794
Some frowned, some smiled.

37:13.250 --> 37:19.997
Some even laughed, and some cried, and then they began to understand.

37:26.063 --> 37:28.505
Friends from within a war zone loved changed me.

37:28.545 --> 37:32.249
It softened my certainty.

37:32.269 --> 37:41.618
It expanded the reach of my empathy, and it reinforced the truth that I am loved and so are they.

37:43.746 --> 37:52.561
That is a full gospel kind of boundary-breaking, solidarity-making, captives-liberating, creative kind of costly love.

37:52.761 --> 37:55.646
And it's the love that's changing me.

37:55.726 --> 37:57.589
It's the love that's transforming us.

37:58.090 --> 38:05.042
And if we live like we believe that this is true, it is the only power that's going to remake our world.

